  "body": "* `brownie` Version: 1.4.0\r\n* `solc` Version: N/A\r\n* Python Version: 3.7.5\r\n* OS: linux\r\n\r\n### What was wrong?\r\nBrownie assumes `solc` will be specified in a projects configuration file, and throws when it is not there:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n$ brownie compile\r\nBrownie v1.4.0 - Python development framework for Ethereum\r\n\r\n  File \"brownie/_cli/__main__.py\", line 57, in main\r\n    importlib.import_module(f\"brownie._cli.{args['<command>']}\").main()\r\n  File \"brownie/_cli/compile.py\", line 28, in main\r\n    project.load(project_path)\r\n  File \"brownie/project/main.py\", line 443, in load\r\n    return Project(name, project_path)\r\n  File \"brownie/project/main.py\", line 139, in __init__\r\n    self.load()\r\n  File \"brownie/project/main.py\", line 147, in load\r\n    self._compiler_config = _load_project_compiler_config(self._path, \"solc\")\r\n  File \"brownie/_config.py\", line 113, in _load_project_compiler_config\r\n    return config_data[\"compiler\"][compiler]\r\nKeyError: 'solc'\r\n```\r\n\r\n### How to fix it\r\nI think it would probably be best if brownie's config files didn't assume any of the keys are there (using some reasonable defaults unless overriden). Also, it would be great if it didn't assume `solc` was a requirement unless it detected it was necessary (for Vyper-only projects), but perhaps that is a different issue.",
